**Sec. 70401 – Enhanced Employer-Provided Child Care Credit**  
The bill raises the employer-provided child care credit from 25 % to 40 % (50 % for eligible small businesses) and doubles the maximum credit to $500,000 ($600,000 for eligible small businesses). It also expands the definition of “eligible small business” to a 5-year gross-receipts test and allows third-party intermediaries to claim the credit. These changes apply to amounts paid or incurred after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70402 – Enhanced Adoption Credit**  
The bill makes the $5,000 adoption credit refundable and subjects it to the regular tax system. It also indexes the credit to inflation starting in 2025, using 2001 as the base year. The refundable portion is excluded from the carryforward rules. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70403 – Indian Tribal Governments and Adoption Credit**  
The bill explicitly includes Indian tribal governments as “states” for purposes of determining if a child has special needs under the adoption credit rules. This change applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70404 – Enhanced Dependent Care Assistance Program**  
The bill raises the employer-provided dependent care assistance program exclusion from $5,000 to $7,500 ($3,750 for married filing separately). This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70405 – Enhanced Child and Dependent Care Tax Credit**  
The bill increases the applicable percentage from 35 % to 50 % for taxpayers with AGI up to $15,000, phases it down to 35 % at $43,000, and further down to 20 % at $75,000 (or $150,000 for joint filers). It also eliminates the age cap for disabled spouses. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70411 – Tax Credit for Contributions to Scholarship Granting Organizations**  
The bill creates a new 30 % non-refundable tax credit for contributions to state-designated scholarship granting organizations (SGOs). Contributions are limited to $1,700 per taxpayer per year and must benefit low-income students (≤300 % of federal poverty line). SGOs must award scholarships to at least 10 students, spend ≥90 % of funds on scholarships, and verify income. Contributions are not deductible under §170. Unused credits carry forward for 5 years. States must certify SGOs annually. This applies to taxable years ending after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70412 – Exclusion for Employer Student Loan Payments**  
The bill permanently extends the exclusion for employer student loan payments, removing the 2026 expiration. It also indexes the $5,250 annual cap to inflation starting in 2026. This applies to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70413 – Expanded 529 Account Qualifications**  
The bill allows 529 plans to cover elementary and secondary school tuition, curriculum materials, tutoring, standardized test fees, dual enrollment costs, and educational therapies for students with disabilities. It also doubles the lifetime limit for K–12 tuition from $10,000 to $20,000. These changes apply to distributions after enactment.

**Sec. 70414 – Postsecondary Credentialing Expenses in 529 Plans**  
The bill expands 529 plans to cover recognized postsecondary credential programs, including apprenticeships, industry-recognized certificates, and state-approved programs. It defines “recognized credentials” to include Department of Defense COOL certifications, registered apprenticeships, and state/federal licenses. These changes apply to distributions after enactment.

**Sec. 70415 – Modified Excise Tax on Private College Investment Income**  
The bill replaces the fixed 1.4 % excise tax on private college endowment income with a tiered rate structure (1.4 %, 4 %, or 8 %) based on student-adjusted endowment thresholds ($500k–$750k or $750k–$2M). It also subjects federally subsidized royalty income to the tax and expands reporting requirements. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70416 – Expanded Tax on Excess Compensation in Tax-Exempt Organizations**  
The bill extends the $1M cap on excess compensation to all employees of tax-exempt organizations, including former employees who were covered after 2016. This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70421 – Permanent Renewal and Enhancement of Opportunity Zones**  
The bill makes Opportunity Zone designations permanent, with new designations every 10 years (starting July 1, 2026). It repeals the special rule for Puerto Rico and removes the contiguous tract requirement. It also simplifies the 10-year holding period for gain deferral and introduces qualified rural opportunity funds (90 % assets in rural zones). These changes apply to investments made after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70422 – Permanent Enhancement of Low-Income Housing Tax Credit**  
The bill permanently increases the state housing credit ceiling to 12.5 % of qualified basis (from 11.25 %) and simplifies the tax-exempt bond financing test. These changes apply to buildings placed in service after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70423 – Permanent Extension of New Markets Tax Credit**  
The bill makes the New Markets Tax Credit permanent, removing the 2025 expiration. It also allows unused limitations to be carried forward for 5 years (with a 2025 lookback). These changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70424 – Permanent Reinstatement of Partial Charitable Deduction for Non-Itemizers**  
The bill permanently restores the $1,000 ($2,000 married) charitable deduction for non-itemizers. This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70425 – 0.5 % Floor on Charitable Deductions for Individuals**  
The bill imposes a 0.5 % AGI floor on charitable deductions for individuals, applying after subparagraphs (D) through (G). Unused deductions carry forward for 5 years. This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70426 – 1 % Floor on Charitable Deductions for Corporations**  
The bill imposes a 1 % AGI floor on corporate charitable deductions, with a 10 % cap. Unused deductions carry forward for 5 years. This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70427 – Permanent Increase in Distilled Spirits Tax Cap**  
The bill permanently raises the cap on the cover over tax for distilled spirits from $13.25 to $13.25 (no change) but applies it to imports after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70428 – Nonprofit Community Development in Remote Native Villages**  
The bill exempts qualifying fisheries activities in the Bering Sea and Aleutian Islands from unrelated business income tax (UBIT) for entities identified in the Magnuson-Stevens Act. It also grants tax-exempt status to wholly owned subsidiaries transferring these activities within 18 months. This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70429 – Charitable Deduction for Native Alaskan Subsistence Whaling**  
The bill permanently increases the charitable deduction cap for Native Alaskan subsistence whaling from $10,000 to $50,000. This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70430 – Exception to Percentage-of-Completion Method for Residential Construction**  
The bill extends the percentage-of-completion method exception to all residential construction contracts (not just “home construction”) and lengthens the recognition period from 2 to 3 years. It also applies the exception to the alternative minimum tax. These changes apply to contracts entered into after enactment.

**Sec. 70431 – Expansion of Qualified Small Business Stock Gain Exclusion**  
The bill phases in a 50 %–75 %–100 % exclusion for QSB stock gains held 3–5 years (50 % for 3 years, 75 % for 4 years, 100 % for 5+ years). It raises the per-issuer cap to $15M (indexed after 2026) and the aggregate cap to $75M (indexed after 2026). These changes apply to taxable years beginning after enactment.

**Sec. 70432 – Repeal of De Minimis Rules for Third-Party Network Transactions**  
The bill restores the pre-2021 de minimis exception, requiring reporting only for payments exceeding $20,000 and 200 transactions. It also applies this threshold to backup withholding. These changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70433 – Increased Threshold for Information Reporting**  
The bill raises the 1099 reporting threshold from $600 to $2,000 and indexes it for inflation after 2026. It also aligns backup withholding thresholds with the new $2,000 limit. These changes apply to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70434 – Treatment of Qualified Sound Recording Productions**  
The bill adds qualified sound recording productions to the §181 election, allowing costs to be expensed up to $150,000 per production. It also grants bonus depreciation for these productions and defines “qualified sound recording production” as U.S.-made recordings. These changes apply to productions commencing in taxable years ending after enactment.

**Sec. 70435 – Exclusion of Interest on Rural/Ag Loans**  
The bill excludes 25 % of interest income from qualified rural or agricultural real estate loans made by banks, insurers, and certain financial entities. It also coordinates with §265 to treat 25 % of the loan as tax-exempt. These changes apply to taxable years ending after enactment.

**Sec. 70436 – Reduction of Transfer and Making Taxes for Certain Firearms**  
The bill eliminates the $200 transfer and making taxes for standard firearms, retaining the $200 tax only for machineguns and destructive devices. These changes apply to calendar quarters beginning more than 90 days after enactment.

**Sec. 70437 – Capital Gains Treatment for Farmland Sales**  
The bill creates a new §1062 allowing farmers to elect installment sale treatment for gains from selling farmland used for farming for 10 years. The gain is taxed in 4 equal installments over 4 years. These changes apply to sales in taxable years beginning after enactment.

**Sec. 70438 – Extension of Disaster-Related Casualty Loss Rules**  
The bill extends the special rules for disaster-related personal casualty losses (from the 2020 Act) through the date of enactment. These changes apply retroactively.

**Sec. 70439 – Restoration of REIT Subsidiary Asset Test**  
The bill raises the asset test for REIT subsidiaries from 20 % to 25 %. This applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025. [end of text]


